review_blob: 0.5L can. Pours pale golden with a big, creamy head that slowly diminishes, leaving a fair lacing. Notes of hay in the aroma. It has a light sweet flavor and a mild bitter finish. The Mouthfeel iis OK, but the carbonation is maybe a bit too fizzy. This is a cheap beer, produced for a large chain of convenience stores in Norway. Not a great pilsener.

0.5 can. Puors golden, OK head that all but disappears. The aroma is sort of skunky and/or stale, but fortunately faint. The flavor is sour and it feels a bit metallic. Decent body, but the finish kills this one a bit. There is an unpleasant, lingering aftertaste to this particular sample. This has never been a favorite, but I think ive had Ringnes Pilsners that tasted better.

0.5L can. Pours a nice golden color with a small mostly diminishing head. A faint aroma of yoghurt is all I get. The flavor is a bit sour and finishes a bit bitter. It has a decent mouthfeel, but a tad too watery.

0.5L can. Pours a golden yellow with a big, mostly diminishing head. notes of dried hay, basement and nuts of some sort, somewhat undefineable. The flavor is i bit sour with a light bitterness. The mouthfeel is quite good for a cheap pilsener.

0.44L can. Pours a pitch black with a medium sized, mostly lasting head with very good lacing. The flavor has a good bitterness to it and ends a bit dry. Aromaes of coffee and roasted nuts, notes of earthy yeast. A medium body, thin texture and an short bitter finish.

0.5L can. Pours nice golden yellow with a medium sized, mostly lasting head and nice lacing. The flavour has a light sweetness to it and a nice, medium bitterness afterwards. The palate starts off with a medium body, ending slightly watery. Carbonation is average, borderline soft. It has some notes of citrus and cereal in the aroma. A refreshing and quenching pilsener on a hot summers eve.

Can at home - Pours a typical pale pilsener yellow with a quickly diminishing head. Very little aroma to speak of, some hay and citrus maybe. Light taste with some bitterness. It has a bit of the typical "Grans-taste" to it, but other than that nothin to write home about.

bottle at home - Pours a pale yellow with a medium sized head that slowly disappears. Aromas of grass and citrus. Thin mouthfeel, but foamy ending. Tastes very light and ends dry. One of the better tasting local low alcohol beers in my opinion, but stil too watery and thin.

Batch 207 - Pours black with a small brown, quickly disappearing head. The aroma has notes of alcohol, roasted malt and caramel. Full bodied and potent. The taste of it is somewhat distant and anonymous at first, but comes in with roasted mallty flavours and dark dark chocolate. A dry bitterness and malty flavour lingers afterwards.
